{
  "query": "How do the effects of retaining crop residues on-site compare with incorporating plant material brought from elsewhere?",
  "relevant_summary": "Comparing the effects of retaining crop residues on-site versus incorporating plant material from elsewhere reveals distinct benefits for each approach. Retaining crop residues on-site consistently reduces water runoff and soil erosion while increasing soil organic carbon, nitrogen levels, microbial biomass, and crop yields (action 907). Incorporating external plant material also increases microbial biomass and soil carbon levels, with straw incorporation showing reduced soil loss though effects vary by soil type (action 910). While crop residue retention provides more predictable benefits for erosion control and water management, external plant amendments offer flexibility in material selection and application timing, with variable outcomes depending on the specific material used.",
